Pressure on states that resisted the administration\'92s broader agenda reinforced the same pattern. Trump publicly demanded an apology from Maine\'92s governor for refusing to implement a federal trans athlete ban, framing her stance as unlawful defiance of federal authority. The demand was symbolic, but it echoed the threats embedded in the election order: governors who diverged from his culture-war and power agenda could expect public shaming and, where possible, financial or regulatory punishment. Federal power, once a shared resource, became a stick to be wielded against disfavored regions and officials. The message was that autonomy would carry a price.\
